</table>
<p><b>Masamune Shirow</b> <span style="font-weight: normal">(<span class="t_nihongo_kanji"><span lang="ja" xml:lang="ja">士郎 正宗</span></span> <span class="t_nihongo_comma" style="display:none">,</span><i><span class="t_nihongo_romaji">Shirō Masamune</span></i><span class="t_nihongo_help noprint"><sup><a href="/wiki/Help:Japanese" title="Help:Japanese"><span class="t_nihongo_icon" style="color: #00e; font: bold 80% sans-serif; text-decoration: none; padding: 0 .1em;">?</span></a></sup></span>)</span> is an internationally renowned <a href="/wiki/Manga" title="Manga">manga</a> artist, born <b>Masanori Ota</b> (太田 まさのり <i>Ōta Masanori</i>)<sup id="cite_ref-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-0" title=""><span>[</span>1<span>]</span></a></sup> on <span class="mw-formatted-date" title="1961-11-23"><span class="mw-formatted-date" title="11-23"><a href="/wiki/November_23" title="November 23">November 23</a></span>, <a href="/wiki/1961" title="1961">1961</a></span>.</p>
<p><i>Masamune Shirow</i> is a <a href="/wiki/Pen_name" title="Pen name">pen name</a>, based on a famous swordsmith, <a href="/wiki/Masamune" title="Masamune">Masamune</a>. He is best known for the manga <i><a href="/wiki/Ghost_in_the_Shell_(manga)" title="Ghost in the Shell (manga)">Ghost in the Shell</a></i>, which has since been turned into three <a href="/wiki/Anime" title="Anime">anime</a> movies, two <a href="/wiki/Anime" title="Anime">anime</a> TV series and several <a href="/wiki/Video_games" title="Video games" class="mw-redirect">video games</a>. Shirow is also popular for creating erotic art.</p>
<p>Born in the <a href="/wiki/Hy%C5%8Dgo_Prefecture" title="Hyōgo Prefecture">Hyōgo Prefecture</a> capital city of <a href="/wiki/Kobe,_Hyogo" title="Kobe, Hyogo" class="mw-redirect">Kobe</a>, he studied oil painting at <a href="/wiki/Osaka_University_of_Arts" title="Osaka University of Arts">Osaka University of Arts</a>. While in college, he developed an interest in manga, which led him to create his own complete work, <i><a href="/wiki/Black_Magic_M-66" title="Black Magic M-66" class="mw-redirect">Black Magic</a></i>, which was published in the manga <a href="/wiki/Fanzine" title="Fanzine">fanzine</a> <i>Atlas</i>. His work caught the eye of <a href="/w/index.php?title=Seishinsha&amp;action=edit&amp;redlink=1" class="new" title="Seishinsha (page does not exist)">Seishinsha</a> President Harumichi Aoki, who offered to publish him.</p>
<p>The result was <i><a href="/wiki/Appleseed_(manga)" title="Appleseed (manga)">Appleseed</a></i>, a full volume of densely-plotted drama taking place in an ambiguous future. The story was a sensation, and won the 1986 <a href="/wiki/Seiun_Award" title="Seiun Award">Seiun Award</a> for Best Manga. After a professional reprint of <i><a href="/wiki/Black_Magic_M-66" title="Black Magic M-66" class="mw-redirect">Black Magic</a></i> and a second volume of <i>Appleseed</i>, he released <i><a href="/wiki/Dominion_(manga)" title="Dominion (manga)" class="mw-redirect">Dominion</a></i> in 1986. Two more volumes of <i>Appleseed</i> followed before he began work on <i><a href="/wiki/Ghost_in_the_Shell" title="Ghost in the Shell">Ghost in the Shell</a></i>.</p>
<p>In 2007, he collaborated again with <a href="/wiki/Production_I.G" title="Production I.G">Production I.G</a> to co-create the original concept for the <a href="/wiki/Anime" title="Anime">anime</a> television series <i><a href="/wiki/Shinreigari/Ghost_Hound" title="Shinreigari/Ghost Hound" class="mw-redirect">Shinreigari/Ghost Hound</a></i>, Production I.G's 20th year anniversary project.</p>
<p>A further original collaboration with <a href="/wiki/Production_I.G" title="Production I.G">Production I.G</a> began airing in April, 2008, titled <i><a href="/wiki/Real_Drive" title="Real Drive">Real Drive</a></i>.</p>
